%claude:
To study all these topics concretely, I need a specific
implementation. Like for most books in \principia, I chose
\plan because its libraries are simple, small, elegant,
open source, and they form together a coherent set.
%
In \plan, the capabilities described above are spread across
five libraries:
[[libc]] (the C standard library: memory, strings, Unicode,
formatted I/O, system calls, math, networking),
[[libbio]] (buffered I/O),
[[libregexp]] (regular expressions),
[[libflate]] (compression),
and [[libthread]] (cooperative threads with channels).
Together, they total roughly 15\,000 lines of C
and a few hundred lines of assembly---small enough
to explain in full detail in a single book.

%claude:
Most of the code in this book is {portable} C---the same
source is shared between the ARM and x86 ports. Some
routines are written in assembly, either because there is
no choice (the C runtime entry point, context switching,
atomic operations) or for performance (memory and string
operations). For those I focus on the ARM versions, since
ARM is the architecture used throughout \principia.
Sections covering ARM-specific code are marked with ``(ARM)''
in their title.

\section{Other core libraries}

Here are a few core libraries that I considered for this book, but
which I ultimately discarded:
\begin{itemize}

\item GNU Libc\furl{https://www.gnu.org/software/libc/} (also called
[[glibc]]) is the standard C library on most Linux distributions.
It is a full POSIX-compliant implementation, supporting dozens of
architectures and locales.
However, its codebase is enormous: over 1\,000\,000 LOC,
which is almost two orders of magnitude more code than \plan's
[[libc]]. It also cannot be linked statically in practice:
[[glibc]] internally uses [[dlopen]] (dynamic loading) for NSS
(Name Service Switch), a pluggable system that lets
administrators choose how hostnames, users, and passwords
are resolved at runtime. Because NSS loads shared libraries,
any program linked against [[glibc]]---even statically---may
still need dynamic linking at runtime, making it impossible
to produce a truly self-contained binary.

\item musl\furl{https://musl.libc.org/} is a lightweight,
POSIX-compliant C library designed for static linking on Linux.
It is much smaller than [[glibc]] (around 90\,000 LOC) and is
known for clean, readable code. It would have been a reasonable
alternative to the \plan libraries, but it is still significantly
larger and is tied to the Linux kernel's system call interface.
%by must authors I think: http://www.etalabs.net/compare_libcs.html 
% (musl vs uClibc vs dietlibc vs glibc)

\item dietlibc\furl{https://www.fefe.de/dietlibc/} is a minimal
C library by Felix von Leitner, optimized for producing the
smallest possible statically-linked executables. The project
appears to be largely unmaintained.

\item uClibc\furl{https://uclibc-ng.org/} (originally ``microcontroller
C library'') was designed for embedded Linux systems with limited
memory. It is much smaller than [[glibc]] and
supports many architectures, but targets Linux specifically.
The project was largely dormant for years before being revived
as uClibc-ng. For embedded use it has been mostly superseded
by musl.

\item Plauger's {\em The Standard C Library}~\cite{plauger}
is the closest predecessor to what this book attempts: a
line-by-line explanation of every function in a C standard
library. The complete source code is printed in the book
(but is not open source). Plauger's implementation targets
the C89 standard and is portable across platforms. However,
it covers only the ANSI subset---no threading, no networking,
no Unicode---and predates UTF-8 entirely.

\item The C library from Hanson's {\em C Interfaces and
Implementations}~\cite{cii} provides a well-designed set of
abstract data types (arenas, lists, tables, rings, sequences)
that are notably absent from \plan's [[libc]]. However, it is
a pedagogical library, not a system library---it builds on top
of an existing [[libc]] rather than replacing it.

\end{itemize}


\begin{figure}[]\centering
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{lineage}
\caption{C standard libraries timeline}
\label{fig:lineage}
\end{figure}

%claude:
Figure~\ref{fig:lineage} presents a timeline of major C standard library
implementations. The \plan libraries are highlighted in red: [[libc]],
[[libbio]], and [[libthread]]. They descend from the original UNIX~libc
(1973) but diverge significantly---\plan's [[libc]] was designed from
scratch for UTF-8, uses [[errstr]] instead of [[errno]], and is far
smaller than POSIX-compliant alternatives like GNU~libc or musl.

%claude:
The threading lineage is particularly interesting: \plan's [[libthread]]
drew on Hoare's CSP (1978) to provide cooperative threads with channels,
a model that later inspired Go's goroutines directly.
The buffered I/O lineage runs from Lesk's [[stdio]] (1975)
through AT\&T's [[sfio]] to \plan's [[libbio]], each iteration
simplifying the API.

%claude:
I think the \plan core libraries represent the best compromise
for this book: they cover the essential components---memory allocation,
string manipulation, buffered I/O, Unicode, and threading---while
remaining small enough to explain in full detail.

