\section{Getting started}

%claude:
The core libraries are normally compiled as part of the
full \plan build (see \urlinstall). To cross-compile the
ARM libraries from a Linux or macOS host:
\begin{verbatim}
$ cd lib_core/libc
$ objtype=arm mk all
\end{verbatim}
%
The linker [[5l]] automatically links [[libc]] into every
program, so you do not need to specify it explicitly.
To use [[libthread]] or [[libregexp]], pass them on the
[[5l]] command line:
\begin{verbatim}
$ 5c myprogram.c
$ 5l -lthread myprogram.5
\end{verbatim}

%claude:
Most of the libraries described in this book are also available
through plan9port\furl{https://9fans.github.io/plan9port/} and
Goken9cc\furl{https://github.com/aryx/goken9cc},
where they are compiled natively on Linux, macOS, or Windows
using gcc or clang. In particular, both provide [[libc]]
(with the UTF-8 string functions, [[print()]], [[malloc()]]),
[[libbio]], [[libregexp]], and [[libthread]]---so programs
using these libraries can run outside \plan. Some functions
that depend on \plan kernel features (e.g., [[rfork()]],
[[/dev/cons]]) are emulated or adapted for the host OS.

\section{Requirements}

% see intro(2), overview of many libs

%claude:
Because this book is made of C source code, you will need
a good knowledge of the C programming language.
Kernighan and Ritchie's {\em The C Programming
Language}~\cite{k-r} and Harbison and Steele's {\em C: A
Reference Manual}~\cite{c-ref-manual} are both excellent
references; they also describe the standard library's API
(function signatures, semantics, edge cases), which
complements this book's focus on the implementation.
Some library code makes heavy use of pointer arithmetic and
bit manipulation (especially the memory allocator), so
comfort with low-level C is important.
%
Reading Plauger's {\em The Standard C
Library}~\cite{plauger}---the only other book that explains
a complete C library implementation line by line---is useful
background but not required. Hanson's {\em C Interfaces and
Implementations}~\cite{cii} is also relevant for its
treatment of arenas, assertions, and abstract data types.

%claude:
Reading the \book{Kernel} is helpful but not required: the
kernel implements the system calls that the libraries wrap,
and understanding both sides gives a fuller picture. The
\book{Assembler} is useful for the few routines written in
ARM assembly (e.g., [[memset]], [[getcallerpc]]).
