\section{Software architecture}

% note that libc should be thread-safe, malloc use locks!

% take common.ml structure for the TOC of this document?

%claude:
Unlike a compiler or a build system, a library is not a pipeline.
It is a collection of largely independent components that programs
link against and call as needed. The ``architecture'' of a C
library is therefore better understood as a layering:
%
\begin{enumerate}
\item {\em System call wrappers} (in [[9sys/]] and [[9syscall/]])
provide thin assembly stubs that trap into the kernel for
[[open]], [[read]], [[write]], [[rfork]], [[exec]], [[brk]],
[[rendezvous]], etc.

\item {\em Core services} built on those system calls:
the memory allocator ([[malloc]]/[[free]] on top of [[sbrk]]),
buffered I/O ([[Biobuf]] on top of [[read]]/[[write]]),
formatted output ([[print]] on top of [[write]]),
locking ([[qlock]] on top of [[rendezvous]]),
and networking ([[dial]]/[[announce]] on top of [[open]]/[[read]]/[[write]]
to [[/net/]]).

\item {\em Pure computation}: string manipulation, math functions,
regular expressions, and 9P marshalling.
These do not use system calls at all---though they may
call [[malloc]], which itself may call the [[sbrk]] system
call to grow the heap.

\item {\em [[libthread]]}: a layer on top of everything else,
providing cooperative threads, channels, and IO procs. When
linked in, [[libthread]] replaces [[main]], [[exits]],
[[dial]], [[_assert]], and [[_sysfatal]] with thread-aware
versions.
\end{enumerate}
%
The key dependency is that nearly everything depends on the
memory allocator, and the allocator itself depends on locks.
In \plan, [[rfork(RFMEM)]] creates a new process that shares
its parent's memory---effectively a system-level thread.
Since two such processes can call [[malloc]] concurrently,
the allocator must be thread-safe (see the discussion of
thread safety versus reentrancy in the Principles section).
More generally, [[libc]] functions that use global state
(e.g., [[syslog]], [[atexit]]) protect it with locks, making
\plan's [[libc]] safe for use with shared-memory processes.
[[libthread]]'s channels add another layer, depending on
locks, atomic operations, and the [[rendezvous]] system call.

%yoann: maybe ASCII diagram with those layers?
%claude:
The following diagram summarizes this layering:
\begin{verbatim}
  +-----------------------------------------------------------+
  |  libthread: threads, channels, alt, IO procs              |
  |  (replaces main, exits, dial, _sysfatal when linked in)   |
  +------------------+----------------------------------------+
  |  Core services   |  Pure computation                      |
  |  malloc/free     |  strings, runes, UTF-8                 |
  |  Biobuf          |  regexp, math, compression             |
  |  print/fprint    |  9P marshalling                        |
  |  qlock, dial     |                                        |
  +------------------+----------------------------------------+
  |  System call wrappers (9sys/, 9syscall/)                   |
  |  open, read, write, rfork, exec, brk, rendezvous, ...     |
  +-----------------------------------------------------------+
  |  Kernel                                                    |
  +-----------------------------------------------------------+
\end{verbatim}

\section{Book structure}

%claude: %trans:
You now have enough background to understand the source code
of the \plan core libraries.
%toc:
The rest of the book is organized in five parts.
%
Part~I ({\em Foundations}) covers the bedrock:
the core types and data structures in Chapter~\ref{chap:core-ds},
the system call interface in Chapter~\ref{chap:user-kernel},
the C runtime entry point [[_main()]] in Chapter~\ref{chap:main},
and memory management (Chapter~\ref{chap:memops} for low-level
operations, Chapter~\ref{chap:malloc} for the [[malloc]] allocator).
%
Part~II ({\em Data Processing}) covers pure computation:
strings in Chapter~\ref{chap:strings} (C strings, runes, and UTF-8),
regular expressions in Chapter~\ref{chap:regexp},
mathematics in Chapter~\ref{chap:math},
and compression.
%
Part~III ({\em System Services}) covers the library functions
that wrap system calls, roughly one family per chapter:
file I/O in Chapter~\ref{chap:fileio},
buffered I/O in Chapter~\ref{chap:bufio},
directories in Chapter~\ref{chap:dirs},
namespace operations in Chapter~\ref{chap:namespace},
time in Chapter~\ref{chap:time},
process management in Chapter~\ref{chap:fork},
error management in Chapter~\ref{chap:errors},
and security in Chapter~\ref{chap:security}.
%
Part~IV ({\em Concurrency and Communication}) covers
synchronization and IPC:
locks and queuing locks in Chapter~\ref{chap:concurrency},
IPC mechanisms (notes, pipes, 9P) in Chapter~\ref{chap:ipc},
the cooperative thread scheduler and channels in
Chapter~\ref{chap:threads} (the largest chapter in the book),
and networking in Chapter~\ref{chap:network}.
%
Part~V ({\em Debugging and Profiling}) covers
the library support for the \plan debugging and profiling tools
in Chapters~\ref{chap:debugging} and~\ref{chap:profiling}.
%
Finally, Chapter~\ref{chap:conclusion} concludes and gives pointers
to other books in the \principia series.

