%******************************************************************************
\chapter{User/Kernel Bridge}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:user-kernel}

% sys.h, syscall.h
% lib_core/libc/9syscall/*.s and dispatcher in kernel for the sysxxx().
% FIGURE copy one in Principia.nw?

%claude:
With the core types defined, we now turn to how the library
communicates with the kernel. System calls are the boundary
between user space and the kernel.
In this chapter I present the \plan syscall table, the assembly
stubs that invoke them, and how the C and kernel calling
conventions differ. The kernel side of this bridge is covered
in the \book{Kernel}.

\section{The syscall table}

%claude:
The entire \plan kernel interface is defined in a single
header, [[libc/9syscall/sys.h]], shared between the kernel and the C library.
Each syscall is a small integer:
%dup: Kernel.nw
\begin{verbatim}
  #define NOP         0
  /* process */
  #define RFORK       1
  #define EXEC        2
  #define EXITS       3
  #define AWAIT       4
  /* memory */
  #define BRK         5
  /* files */
  #define OPEN        6
  #define CLOSE       7
  #define PREAD       8
  #define PWRITE      9
  #define SEEK       10
  /* directories */
  #define CREATE     11
  #define REMOVE     12
  ...
  /* concurrency */
  #define RENDEZVOUS 32
  #define SEMACQUIRE 33
  ...
  #define ERRSTR     39
\end{verbatim}
%
Only 39 syscalls. Modern Linux has over 400. \plan can get
away with so few because many operations that require
dedicated syscalls on \unix are done through the file
system instead: reading [[/dev/user]] instead of
[[getuid()]], reading [[/env/PATH]] instead of
[[getenv("PATH")]], writing to [[/proc/pid/note]] instead
of [[kill()]].
%
The grouping matches the structure of this book: each
chapter in Parts~III and~IV corresponds to one group of
syscalls.

\section{The assembly stubs (ARM)}

%claude:
Each syscall has a tiny assembly stub in [[9syscall/]].
For example, here is what [[open.s]] looks like on ARM:
\begin{verbatim}
  TEXT open(SB), 1, $0
  MOVW R0, 0(FP)       /* save first arg */
  MOVW $6, R0          /* OPEN = 6 */
  SWI $0               /* trap into kernel */
  RET
\end{verbatim}
%
Every stub follows the same pattern (see
Section~\ref{sec:asm-crash-course}): save [[R0]] to its
reserved slot at \verb+0(FP)+, load the syscall number
into [[R0]], execute [[SWI $0]], and return.
%
These stubs are not written by hand---they are
{\em generated} by the [[mkfile]] in [[9syscall/]],
which reads [[sys.h]], extracts each syscall name and
number, and emits the corresponding assembly file.
This is a nice example of {code generation}: 40 files
produced from a 40-line header.

\section{The calling conventions (ARM)}

%claude:
The C calling convention (described in
Section~\ref{sec:asm-crash-course}) passes the first argument
in [[R0]] and the rest on the stack. But the kernel expects
a {\em different} convention: the syscall number in [[R0]],
and {\em all} arguments on the stack (including the first).
The assembly stub bridges these two conventions:
\begin{verbatim}
  C convention:             Stub transforms:        Kernel sees:
  +----------+              +----------+             +----------+
  | arg2     | 4(FP)        | arg2     | 4(FP)       | arg2     |
  +----------+              +----------+             +----------+
  | (empty)  | 0(FP)  -->   | arg1     | 0(FP)  -->  | arg1     |
  +----------+              +----------+             +----------+
  R0 = arg1                 R0 = syscall#            R0 = syscall#
\end{verbatim}
%
The full path of a system call then looks like this:
\begin{verbatim}
  User C code           Library               Kernel
  -----------           -------               ------
  fd = open("f", 0) --> open.s: SWI $0  --> sysopen()
                     <-- return fd       <-- return fd
\end{verbatim}
%
The kernel's trap handler saves the user registers, reads
the syscall number from [[R0]], indexes into the [[systab]]
dispatch table (see \book{Kernel}), and calls the
corresponding [[sysxxx()]] function. On return, the
result is placed in [[R0]] and the kernel restores
the user registers.
%
Errors are signaled by returning $-1$ and setting the
per-process error string (readable via [[errstr()]]).
This is different from \unix, where [[errno]] is a global
variable set by the C library---in \plan, the kernel itself
sets the error string, and the [[%r]] format verb in
[[print]] reads it directly.

\section{Comparison with \unix}

%claude:
The \plan syscall interface differs from \unix in several ways:
\begin{itemize}
\item {\em Fewer syscalls}: 39 vs.\ 400+ on Linux, because
file operations replace specialized syscalls.
\item {\em No [[ioctl]]}: device control is done by reading
and writing control files (e.g., [[/net/tcp/0/ctl]]).
\item {\em [[pread]]/[[pwrite]]}: the primary I/O syscalls
take an explicit offset, making concurrent access safe.
[[read]]/[[write]] are library wrappers, not syscalls.
\item {\em [[rfork]] instead of [[fork]]+[[clone]]}: a single
syscall with flags for fine-grained resource sharing.
\item {\em String errors}: [[errstr]] instead of [[errno]];
[[exits(char*)]] instead of [[exit(int)]].
\end{itemize}

%******************************************************************************
\chapter{[[_main()]] and [[_exits()]]}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:main}

% arm/main9.s (and main9p.s)

%related: minimal C runtime for Linux
%https://github.com/lpsantil/rt0
%https://blogs.oracle.com/ksplice/entry/hello_from_a_libc_free

%real-world: crt0 for "C runtime 0"?

%claude:
Every \plan program actually starts in [[_main()]] (not [[main()]]),
the C runtime entry point. On \unix systems, this role is played by [[crt0]]
(``C runtime, file 0''---the first object file linked into
every program). Some \unix systems also have [[crt1]] and
[[crti]]/[[crtn]] for additional initialization (e.g.,
constructors, profiling setup), but \plan keeps it simple
with a single [[_main]] that sets up [[argc]]/[[argv]] and
then calls [[main()]]. The name may be confusing: [[_main]] is
the true entry point of the program (the linker sets it as
the default entry point---see \book{Linker}), while
[[main()]] is the user's entry point, called by [[_main]]
after initialization is complete.

This chapter also covers the argument parsing macros and
the [[exits]] function that handles cleanup callbacks before
termination.

\section{[[_main()]] (ARM)}

%yoann: explain assembly, and especially weird SB thing (reference Linker book?)
%claude:
The C runtime entry point must be written in assembly because
it sets up things that C code takes for granted: the static
base register (needed to access any global variable), the
stack frame (needed for local variables and function calls),
and the [[argc]]/[[argv]] arguments (which the kernel places
in a raw format that must be reformatted for C). On \unix,
the equivalent code ([[crt0]]) also initializes the dynamic
linker, thread-local storage, and C++ constructors---\plan
is simpler but the same principle applies.

%claude:
When the kernel starts a new process, it sets [[R0]] to point
to the [[Tos]] structure (shared between user and kernel, used
for profiling and the pid) and places [[argc]] and [[argv]]
on the stack. The layout before [[_main]] runs:
\begin{verbatim}
  Top of stack segment
  +------------------+
  | Tos              |  pid, clock, kcycles, pcycles, Prof
  +------------------+  <-- R0 points here
  |   (gap)          |
  +------------------+
  | argv strings     |  "arg0\0arg1\0..."
  +------------------+
  | argv[N] = nil    |
  | ...              |
  | argv[0]          |  pointers to the strings above
  +------------------+
  | argc             |  number of arguments
  +------------------+  <-- SP (stack pointer)
  Low addresses
\end{verbatim}
%
The [[Tos]] (``top of stack'') structure sits at the very
top of the user stack segment, {\em above} the stack itself.
It is shared between user and kernel and contains fields
like [[pid]] (process ID), [[clock]] (cycle counter for
profiling), [[kcycles]]/[[pcycles]] (kernel/user cycle
counts), and the [[Prof]] structure for profiling data.
The kernel passes its address in [[R0]].
See \book{Kernel} for the full definition.

%yoann: maybe say that no space for ret addr, which is part of C calling convention! hence the need to adjust what the kernel did (why kernel didn't do the right thing directly?)
%claude:
Notice that the kernel's layout has no slot for a return
address---that is not a mistake. In ARM, the return address
is held in R14 (the link register), never pushed to the
stack. However, the C calling convention still reserves
a specific layout for how a callee sees its arguments via FP.
The kernel cannot simply match that layout because it is not
a C caller: it just pushes [[argc]] and [[argv]] at the
initial SP without any calling-convention framing. It is
[[_main]]'s job to bridge this gap.

%yoann: transition paragraph say now mostly ready to show ARM code of _main
%claude:
With the kernel's entry layout understood, we are ready to
read [[_main]] itself. The assembly sets up the SB register,
saves [[Tos]], carves the private storage area from the
frame, and copies [[argc]]/[[argv]] into the positions that
the C calling convention requires before branching to
[[main()]].

<<libc/arm/main9.s>>=
<<constant NPRIVATES(arm)>>
<<constant NOPROF(arm)>>
arg=0
sp=13
sb=12

TEXT    _main(SB), NOPROF, $(16 + NPRIVATES*4)
        MOVW    $setR12(SB), R(sb)
        MOVW    R(arg), _tos(SB)

        <<[[_main()]](arm) setup private storage>>
        <<[[_main()]](arm) adjust argc argv>>

        // user main()
        BL      main(SB)

loop:
        <<[[_main()]](arm) exit (if not done by main)>>

<<[[_main()]](arm) [[_exitstr]] defintion>>
@

%claude:
The first instruction initializes [[R12]] via the
[[setR12]] bootstrap described in
Section~\ref{sec:asm-crash-course}. Until this executes,
no global variable can be accessed.
%
The second instruction saves the [[Tos]] pointer (passed
by the kernel in [[R0]], which is the same than [[R(arg)]] given the definition
of [[arg]]) to the global [[_tos]] (declared
in [[libc.h]] as \verb+extern Tos *_tos+). This works
because [[R12]] was just initialized.

%claude:
The private storage area is carved from the stack frame
(the \verb!$(16 + NPRIVATES*4)! in the [[TEXT]] directive
reserves space). [[_privates]] and [[_nprivates]] are globals
used by [[privalloc()]] to implement per-process private data
(see Chapter~\ref{chap:threads}).
The [[16]] bytes (4~words) are the argument-passing slots
that [[_main]] needs for the functions it calls: the Plan 9
ARM convention requires the caller to reserve stack space
for arguments, so [[_main]]'s frame has room for the
[[argc]]/[[argv]] it will place at \verb+4(R(sp))+/\verb+8(R(sp))+ when calling [[main()]]
(and similarly for the call to [[exits()]]).

<<constant NPRIVATES(arm)>>=
#define NPRIVATES       16
@

<<[[_main()]](arm) setup private storage>>=
MOVW    $p-64(SP), R1
MOVW    R1, _privates(SB)
MOVW    $NPRIVATES, R1
MOVW    R1, _nprivates(SB)
@

%yoann: maybe show adjusted ASCII stack diagram, where see also why -64(SP)? why not use R13 directly there? (or R(sp))?

%claude:
Next (using the register aliases and pseudo-registers
described in Section~\ref{sec:asm-crash-course}),
[[_main]] copies [[argc]] and [[argv]] from the
kernel's stack layout (accessed via [[FP]]) into the
positions expected by the C calling convention for calling
[[main(int argc, char **argv)]]:

<<[[_main()]](arm) adjust argc argv>>=
MOVW    $inargv+0(FP), R(arg)
MOVW    R(arg), 8(R(sp))
MOVW    inargc-4(FP), R(arg)
MOVW    R(arg), 4(R(sp))
@


\begin{verbatim}
  High addresses
  Kernel's layout:                _main's frame (for calling main):
  +------------------+
  | argv strings     |
  +------------------+            +------------------+
  | argv ptrs (FP+0) |  -------> | &argv   8(R(sp)) |
  +------------------+            +------------------+
  | argc      (FP-4) |  -------> | argc    4(R(sp)) |
  +------------------+            +------------------+
                                  | (privates)       |
                                  +------------------+ <-- R13
  Low addresses
\end{verbatim}
%
The left side shows the kernel's original layout. In the
initial diagram above, [[argc]] was at [[SP]]. But
[[_main]]'s [[TEXT]] directive has since allocated a stack
frame (for the private storage shown on the right), pushing
[[R13]] down. The kernel's data is now above the frame and
is reached via [[FP]]: [[argc]] at \verb+FP-4+ and
[[argv]] at \verb+FP+0+ point to the same memory
locations as before, just accessed with a different base.
%
[[_main]] copies these values into \verb+4(R(sp))+ and
\verb+8(R(sp))+, which are where [[main(int argc, char **argv)]]
expects its arguments.

If [[main]] returns (instead of calling [[exits]]),
[[_main]] calls \verb+exits("main")+ in a loop. The
string \verb+"main"+ signals that the program ended by
falling off the end of [[main]] rather than exiting
explicitly.

<<[[_main()]](arm) exit (if not done by main)>>=
MOVW    $_exitstr<>(SB), R(arg)
MOVW    R(arg), 4(R(sp))
BL      exits(SB)
// unreachable
// force loading of div?
BL      _div(SB)
B       loop
@

%claude:
The [[DATA]]/[[GLOBL]] directives define the exit string
\verb+"main"+ as a global data symbol. The [[BL _div]]
at the end is a linker trick: it forces the integer
division routine to be linked in, since many programs
need it but the linker might otherwise omit it.

<<[[_main()]](arm) [[_exitstr]] defintion>>=
DATA    _exitstr<>+0(SB)/4, $"main"
GLOBL   _exitstr<>+0(SB), $5
@

<<constant NOPROF(arm)>>=
#define NOPROF 1 // see 5.out.h
@

%yoann: maybe reference _main9p.s when enable profiling
%claude:
When a program is linked with profiling enabled ([[5l -p]]),
the linker uses [[_main9p.s]] instead, which calls
[[_profmain()]] before [[main()]] to initialize the
profiling infrastructure (see Chapter~\ref{chap:profiling}).

\section{Command-line arguments: [[ARGBEGIN()]], [[ARGEND()]]}

%claude:
[[ARGBEGIN]]/[[ARGEND]] are the standard \plan idiom for
parsing command-line flags. The macro expands to a [[for]]
loop that scans each argument starting with \verb+-+, decoding
flag characters one at a time with [[chartorune]] (so flags
can be Unicode). The special argument \verb+--+ terminates
flag processing. [[ARGF]] and [[EARGF]] extract the next
argument for flags that take a value.

<<signature global argv0>>=
extern char *argv0;
@

<<macro [[ARGBEGIN]]>>=
#define ARGBEGIN    for((argv0||(argv0=*argv)),argv++,argc--;\
                argv[0] && argv[0][0]=='-' && argv[0][1];\
                argc--, argv++) {\
                char *_args, *_argt;\
                Rune _argc;\
                _args = &argv[0][1];\
                if(_args[0]=='-' && _args[1]==0){\
                    argc--; argv++; break;\
                }\
                _argc = 0;\
                while(*_args && (_args += chartorune(&_argc, _args)))\
                switch(_argc)
@
% unicode handling!

<<macro [[ARGEND]]>>=
#define ARGEND      SET(_argt);USED(_argt,_argc,_args);}USED(argv, argc);
@


<<macro [[ARGF]]>>=
#define ARGF()      (_argt=_args, _args="",\
                (*_argt? _argt: argv[1]? (argc--, *++argv): 0))
@

<<macro [[EARGF]]>>=
#define EARGF(x)    (_argt=_args, _args="",\
                (*_argt? _argt: argv[1]? (argc--, *++argv): ((x), abort(), (char*)0)))
@
% Error-aware ARGF

<<macro [[ARGC]]>>=
#define ARGC()      _argc
@

%yoann: maybe give quick example of use of those macros and ASCII diagram explaining the state of those _argt _argc and their meaning and evolutions? Whatever to help understand those macros
%claude:
A typical use looks like:
\begin{verbatim}
  ARGBEGIN{
  case 'd':  debug = 1;       break;
  case 'o':  ofile = ARGF();  break;
  default:   usage();
  }ARGEND
\end{verbatim}
%
For the command line \verb+prog -d -o foo bar+, the macro
iterates over \verb+-d+ and \verb+-o+. On each iteration,
[[_args]] points to the flag characters after the \verb+-+,
[[_argc]] holds the current flag rune (decoded via
[[chartorune]]), and [[_argt]] is used by [[ARGF]] to
extract the flag's argument (\verb+foo+ for \verb+-o+).
After [[ARGEND]], [[argv]] points to the remaining arguments
(\verb+bar+) and [[argc]] is updated accordingly.

\section{Syscall: [[_exits()]]}

%yoann: explain syscall really in sys.h with syscall code, but also declared in syscall.h included from libc.h for C typechecking. The actual func is defined in assembly (via stub as explained before)
%claude:
Each syscall has two definitions. The numeric code
([[EXITS=3]], [[OPEN=6]], etc.) lives in [[9syscall/sys.h]]
and is used only by the assembly stubs. The C-level
signature ([[void _exits(char*)]]) is declared in
[[syscall.h]] which is included from [[libc.h]]---so any
[[.c]] file that includes [[libc.h]] gets type-checked
against the correct prototype. The implementation itself
is the assembly stub generated by [[9syscall/mkfile]].

<<signatures process syscall>>=
extern	void	_exits(char*);
@

% ugly but special code in 9syscall/mkfile to rename call to
% EXITS syscall to _exits instead of exits because probably wanted to
% add special code around _exits after and wanted to be backward
% compatible with previous programs already using exits() in their code.

%yoann: explain why _exits() and not _exits syscall? Also maybe first syscall so maybe show ARM code generated from 9syscall/ by mkfile?
%claude:
The raw system call is called [[_exits]] (with a leading
underscore) rather than [[exits]] so that the library can
wrap it with cleanup logic (running [<atexit()>] callbacks)
in the [<exits()>] function below. 

%claude:
This is actually the only \plan system call that uses this
underscore convention---most other system calls ([[open]],
[[pread]], [[rfork]], etc.) are used directly without a
wrapper. [[exits]] is special because it needs to run
cleanup callbacks before terminating.

%yoann: now that User/Kernel bridge is before, maybe show concrete code of _exits to make things more concrete?
%claude:
The assembly stub for [[_exits]] follows the pattern described
in Chapter~\ref{chap:user-kernel}: it saves the argument
(the exit string pointer, which arrived in [[R0]]) to the
frame at \verb+0(FP)+, loads the syscall number [[EXITS=3]]
into [[R0]], and executes [[SWI $0]].
This is all the user-space code there is---the kernel's
[[sysexits()]] does the actual process teardown.

%yoann: show actual assembly ARM for _exits.s, we already saw one in previous chapter, it is ok to repeat things once
%claude:
Here is the actual ARM stub for [[_exits]], following the
same pattern as [[open.s]] in Chapter~\ref{chap:user-kernel}:
\begin{verbatim}
  TEXT _exits(SB), 1, $0
  MOVW R0, 0(FP)       /* save exit string pointer */
  MOVW $3, R0           /* EXITS = 3 */
  SWI $0                /* trap into kernel */
  RET                   /* never reached */
\end{verbatim}
%
The [[RET]] is never reached because the kernel destroys
the process. It is there because the assembler requires
every [[TEXT]] block to end with a [[RET]].

%yoann: maybe quickly give semantic of _exits()? give an idea of what it does
%claude:
[[_exits(s)]] terminates the calling process immediately,
passing the string [[s]] as its exit status (readable by
the parent via [[await()]]). The empty string \verb+""+ (or
[[nil]]) conventionally means success; any other string
signals failure. Internally, the kernel's [[sysexits()]]
copies the string from user space and calls [[pexit()]],
which frees file descriptors, namespace, and segments,
posts a wait message to the parent, and then---after
switching to the CPU's main stack---releases the MMU state
and returns the [[Proc]] slot to the free pool.
See \book{Kernel} for the full details.

%claude: %unix:
In \unix, [[exit()]] takes an integer status code (0 for
success, non-zero for failure), and the parent decodes it
via macros like [[WIFEXITED]] and [[WEXITSTATUS]]. The
mapping from number to meaning is program-specific and
often undocumented---you need to read the man page to know
that exit code~2 means [[ENOENT]] (``no such file'').
\plan's string-based exit is self-documenting: the parent
sees \verb+"file not found"+ directly.

\section{[[exits()]] and [[atexit()]]}

%claude:
[<exits()>] runs registered cleanup callbacks before calling
the [[_exits]] system call. The [<onex>] table stores up to
33 callback/pid pairs (see the [<Onex>] struct definition).
The pid field exists because after
[[rfork(RFMEM)]], parent and child share memory (including
[[onex]]) but should only run their own callbacks---each
process checks [[getpid()]] before invoking a handler.

<<global [[onex]]>>=
Onex onex[NEXIT];
@
<<constant [[NEXIT]]>>=
#define NEXIT   33
@

<<struct [[Onex]]>>=
struct Onex{
    void    (*f)(void); // callback
    int pid;
};
@
% Onex.pid because some fork can still share memory
% but we want each fork to run separate callbacks when really
% exits.


% profile is turned off around this function
<<function [[exits]]>>=
void
exits(char *s)
{
    int i, pid;
    void (*f)(void);

    pid = getpid();
    for(i = NEXIT-1; i >= 0; i--)
        if((f = onex[i].f) && pid == onex[i].pid) {
            onex[i].f = nil;
            (*f)();
        }
    _exits(s);
}
@

%yoann: explain why for loop in decrement instead of increment
%yoann: explain why called Onex, seems cryptic
%claude:
The loop runs in reverse (from [[NEXIT-1]] down to 0) so
that callbacks are invoked in LIFO order---the last one
registered runs first, mirroring how constructors and
destructors are paired in C++. The name [[Onex]] is short
for ``on exit'' (as in [[atexit]]---``at exit''), and
[[onex]] is the array of registered callbacks.
%
A subtle detail: \verb+onex[i].f = nil+ is set {\em before}
calling the callback. This prevents infinite recursion
if the callback itself calls [[exits]].
%
The [[pid == onex[i].pid]] check is important: after
[[rfork(RFMEM)]], parent and child share the same [[onex]]
array. Without the check, both processes would run all
callbacks on exit---flushing the same buffers twice, closing
the same file descriptors twice, or freeing the same memory
twice. Most cleanup callbacks are not idempotent, so this
would crash or corrupt data. The pid check ensures each
process only runs the callbacks {\em it} registered. A
child process that needs its own cleanup can call [[atexit]]
after the fork.


<<global [[onexlock]]>>=
static Lock onexlock;
@

%yoann: say See Section X for concurrency primitives.
%yoann: exlain atexit
%claude:
The [[onexlock]] protects the [[onex]] array from concurrent
access by shared-memory processes (see
Chapter~\ref{chap:concurrency} for how [[Lock]] works).

%claude:
[[atexit()]] registers a callback to be called when the
program exits. It scans the [[onex]] array for an empty
slot, records the current pid (so that after
[[rfork(RFMEM)]], only the process that registered the
callback will run it), and stores the function pointer.
It returns 1 on success, 0 if the table is full.

<<function [[atexit]]>>=
int
atexit(void (*f)(void))
{
    int i;

    lock(&onexlock);
    for(i=0; i<NEXIT; i++)
        if(onex[i].f == nil) {
            onex[i].pid = getpid();
            onex[i].f = f;
            unlock(&onexlock);
            return 1;
        }
    unlock(&onexlock);
    return 0;
}
@

