%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Mathematics}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:math}

%http://developerblog.redhat.com/2015/01/02/improving-math-performance-in-glibc/

% _div and _mod are in Assembler.nw appendix

% "Computer Approximations, by Hart, Chenney, Lawson, ...
% lib by Sun with all those s_xxx.c, w_xxx.c (see kernel-snowflake/lib/m/)

%claude:
The math library provides the standard transcendental functions
([[sin]], [[cos]], [[exp]], [[log]], [[sqrt]], etc.) plus
integer arithmetic helpers and number parsing.
The integer division and modulus routines ([[_div]], [[_mod]])
are in assembly because the ARM has no hardware divide
instruction (see \book{Assembler}).

%claude:
The polynomial coefficients used throughout this chapter come
from Hart et al.'s {\em Computer Approximations}~\cite{hart},
a classic reference that tabulates thousands of {minimax}
rational approximations for mathematical functions.
A minimax approximation is a polynomial (or ratio of
polynomials) whose coefficients are chosen to minimize the
{\em maximum} error over a given range---giving the best
worst-case accuracy for a given polynomial degree. This is
why the coefficients in this chapter look like magic numbers:
they were computed by optimization algorithms, not derived
by hand.
%
For a broader treatment of numerical algorithms in C---including
root finding, interpolation, integration, and random number
generation---see Press et al.'s {\em Numerical
Recipes}~\cite{numerical-recipes}, which covers much of the
same ground as this chapter but in far greater depth.

